@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi ...Fixed rate goes up when Fed interest rates rise and down when they fall. Inflation rate rises when CPI goes up and falls when it goes down. @SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi Dude. There are two rates: fixed and inflation. So the average real return CANNOT be negative; that's the entire point (and are even better if purchased when the fixed rate was higher)...

@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi So I-bond investors are always guaranteed by the full faith and credit of the US Fed to have a real return of roughly zero, and even better if purchased when the nominal rate is higher, then held during inflationary periods. The same cannot be said of any other asset.

@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi 🙄 Again, the rate is set every six months, based on what CPI was during the previous six. Of course CPI fluctuates, but that also means the interest rate can be higher than the current CPI at times.

@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi Hahah, what. I-Bonds are pegged to CPI, so even when the nominal rate is zero, the "other half" is guaranteed to keep up with inflation, adjusted every six months. Currently paying 7.12% in risk-free interest. So horrible.

@rhett_baylor @maxpashman Both employee and employer literally contributes  FICA (SS and Medicare) every paycheck and SS is the main source of retirement and disability funds for millions of Americans. Claiming we'll "never see" it, if we live long enough, is ridiculous.

@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi Well yeah, inflation is outside our control. No asset is guaranteed to keep up except Series I Bonds. Main point of bonds is they're a great diversifier to equities, and income is secondary.
@SellToOpen007 @FiSurgi Bonds always have positive returns if held to maturity.
